<TITLE> India leaders warned of militant attack risk </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Mar 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. The sources of reports are in brackets. Authorities are worried that senior politicians may be on a hit list of Pakistan-based militant groups during the election campaign. Possible targets include Congress Party president Sonia Gandhi and Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) leader L.K. Advani. Anonymous security officials said there has been increased "chatter" from militants groups of a possible attack. (Mail Today, Times of India) Congress party announced a seat-sharing agreement with the regional JMM party in Jharkhand for the elections. Congress will contest seven seats, the same as in the 2004 vote. The deal sidelines another Congress ally, the RJD party led by cabinet minister Lalu Prasad, and could increase tensions within the ruling coalition. (All newspapers) In Orissa, the Biju Janata Dal (BJD), which snapped ties with the BJP earlier this month, says it will trying to create an alternative to Congress and the Hindu nationalists -- perhaps giving a boost to the national Third Front group of regional parties. WHAT NEWSPAPERS SAY "The fluctuations of Congress are swinging as wildly as the stock markets on a day of free fall." "If an out of depth and demoralised BJP was the political screen saver the last weekend, the characters are now beginning to swap places."(The Economic Times) "At first sight it would appear ... it is now the turn of the Congress Party to suffer jolts ahead of the general elections.
